## OpenEnv Compliance

| Requirement | Implementation |
|---|---|
| `reset()` | `env/environment.py` → `TicketTriageEnv.reset()` |
| `step(action)` | `env/environment.py` → `TicketTriageEnv.step()` |
| `state()` | `env/environment.py` → `TicketTriageEnv.state()` |
| Typed models | `env/models.py` → `TriageObservation`, `TriageAction`, `TriageReward` |
| `openenv.yaml` | Root of project |
| 3 tasks | easy / medium / hard with own graders |
| Scores 0–1 | All graders return float in [0.0, 1.0] |
| Deterministic | Graders are pure functions, `seed=42` |

## Environment Variables

| Variable | Purpose | Example |
|---|---|---|
| `GROQ_API_KEY` | Primary backend key (Groq) | `gsk_...` |
| `GEMINI_API_KEY` | Secondary backend key (Google) | `AIza...` |
| `API_BASE_URL` | OpenAI-compatible API base URL | `https://api.openai.com/v1` |
| `MODEL_NAME` | Model identifier | `llama-3.3-70b-versatile` |
| `OPENAI_API_KEY`| Token for OpenAI/OpenRouter | `sk-...` |
| `HF_TOKEN` | Bearer token for HF Inference | `hf_...` |

---

## 🧠 Hybrid Agentic Architecture

The system employs a multi-tiered decision logic designed for maximum reliability and performance:

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[Incoming Ticket] --> B{LLM Path?}
    B -->|Yes| C[Groq Llama 3.3]
    C -->|Fail| D[Gemini 1.5 Flash]
    D -->|Fail| E[OpenAI / OpenRouter]
    E -->|Fail| F[SFT Baseline]
    B -->|No Key| F
    F --> G[Categorization & Routing]
    C --> G
    D --> G
    E --> G
    G --> H[Shadow RL Reward Calculation]
    H --> I[Action Submission]
```

### LLM Agent Fallback Tiers

1. **🚀 Groq**: Primary backend (ultra-low latency). Attempted if `GROQ_API_KEY` is set.
2. **♊ Gemini**: Secondary backend. Attempted if `GEMINI_API_KEY` is set and model name includes "gemini".
3. **🌐 OpenAI / Custom**: Tertiary backend. Attempted if `OPENAI_API_KEY` or `HF_TOKEN` is set.
4. **📉 SFT Baseline**: Final fallback. If all LLM providers fail or are unconfigured, the system automatically uses the local TF-IDF + Logistic Regression model.

### Shadow RL

Every `step()` call evaluates all **100 possible actions** (5 categories × 4 priorities × 5 routes) and computes:

```
reward = agent_score - best_possible_score  (always ≤ 0)
```

- `reward = 0.0` → optimal decision
- `reward = -0.4` → agent scored 0.6, best was 1.0

This gives a dense, differentiable training signal that supports:
- Policy gradient methods (reward as advantage)
- Offline RL (logged shadow scores as dataset)
- Imitation learning (best\_action as expert label)
